 with tightly interwoven affective, ethical, social, historical, and cosmological dimensions. Often termed hermetic and obscure, Trakl's poems become more accessible when viewed in relation to the evolution of his methods and concerns across different phases, and the idiosyncrasies of his strangely beautiful later works make sense as elements of a sophisticated system of expression committed to "truth" as a transcendental order. Through close readings of poems covering the span of his lyric output, this study traces the evolution of Trakl's distinctive style and themes while attending closely to biographical and cultural contexts. Richard Millington is Senior Lecturer in German at Victoria University of Wellington (Aotearoa New Zealand). He is the author of Snow from Broken Eyes: Cocaine in the Lives and Works of Three Expressionist Poets (2012).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aGentle Apocalypse.  aGeorg Trakl.  aMeaning.  aPoetry.  aTruth.  aaffective dimensions.  aapocalyptic vision.  abiographical context.  aclose readings.  acosmological dimensions.  acultural context.  aethical dimensions.  ahistorical dimensions.  aintimate poetry.  arustic imagery.  asocial dimensions.  atwentieth-century poetry.  auniversal disintegration.  aworldview.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446090?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446090/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles